{
  "title": "Lockerz brings jazz piano to UK garage",
  "category": "music",
  "author": "Allastair Voss",
  "date": "2026-04-26",
  "image": "/assets/images/artists/lockerz.jpg",
  "body": "Lockerz is a Welsh producer who came up through drum and bass before deciding the swung two-step was a more interesting place to spend a decade. He is trained in jazz piano. You can hear it on every record. The harmonic vocabulary on his Garage Shared releases is doing something most UK garage producers either cannot or will not attempt: actual chord changes, voiced like someone who has spent time at a piano with the lights off, working out what the instrument can hold before it tips into dissonance.\n\n[spotify:artist/1LuS7XrtiwtzvdAnZPC6BN]\n\n\"Pulse\" was the track that announced the project properly. The drums are correct, the bass weight is correct, and then the chords arrive and reroute the whole record. Not decorative jazz vocabulary dropped over a serviceable two-step: harmonic movement that changes the emotional temperature of the track, that gives the production something to lean against. \"Burning\", premiered by DJ Mag, extends that approach into something closer to vocal house, the jazz piano pulling the genre's soulful undertow closer to the surface. \"How it Was\" is the most reflective thing he has put out. Slower, more interior, the kind of track that works at 2am rather than midnight. \"Hitbox\" is the one for the floor.\n\n## The Piano Problem\n\n[img:/assets/images/artists/lockerz-jazz-piano-garage.jpg]\n\nUK garage built itself on a particular sample logic in the late nineties. Pull a soul record, chop it, run it under a two-step. That process produced extraordinary music, from the Craig David era through MJ Cole's more orchestrated approach to the Piano House sound that briefly dominated the early 2000s. The form is durable but it has a limit: most producers don't write the chords themselves. The chords are inherited from the sample source, which means the harmonic language of UK garage has always been secondhand. Lockerz writes the chords. That single fact is the reason Garage Shared built a debut album cycle and a tour around him. The genre needs harmonic writing again.\n\nThe jazz piano training shows in more than chord choice. It shows in the voicings, in where the notes sit in the register, in which intervals are chosen to create tension and which to release it. There is a difference between a producer who has studied jazz piano and a producer who has listened to jazz piano, and that difference is audible in the interval spacing. Jazz piano voicings leave room in the middle registers, which creates a different kind of space in the mix than the more clustered chords that come from non-trained producers borrowing the aesthetic without the theory. Lockerz's chords breathe.\n\nThe drum and bass background matters too. That genre demands an acute sense of rhythmic precision, of exactly where a sound sits in relation to the beat, of the difference between a sound that sits behind the beat and one that sits on it. Coming from drum and bass into garage gives his two-step drums a sharpness and exactness that is not typical of the genre. The swing is there. The tightness is also there. Those are usually in tension.\n\n## The Album and What Comes Next\n\nThe debut album arrived in June 2026, seventeen tracks, all the singles from the year plus material that fills in the spaces between them. BBC Radio 1Xtra's attention has been consistent. Conducta's Kiwi label and the small group of producers genuinely advancing UK garage's vocabulary are the natural peer group.\n\nStart with \"Pulse.\" It tells you immediately what kind of producer this is: someone who has thought hard about what the form can hold and has decided to find out. Stay for \"How it Was,\" which tells you what the music does when it stops trying to move the floor and just wants to move you.\n\n## Wales as Unlikely Origin\n\nBeing Welsh and working in a genre defined by London geography is itself an interesting position. UK garage carries the specific cultural markers of South London and East London: the slang, the fashion, the nightlife geography, the accent in the production that says this was made in a particular postal code. Lockerz doesn't pretend to those markers. The music is clearly garage in its structural choices while being sonically distinct from anything that came out of the specific scene that defined the genre.\n\nWelsh music more broadly has produced a strain of artists who work with full commitment inside genres that aren't native to their geography: the history of Welsh soul and gospel, the unexpectedly deep hip-hop scenes in Cardiff and Swansea, the post-punk lineage that runs through Wales differently than it runs through England. Lockerz's jazz training is a kind of musical bilingualism: the formal training of classical European music, the popular culture sensibility of UK dance, both applied to a genre that was built entirely without either.\n\nThe debut album closes with an extended piano piece that has nothing to do with garage. It just sits there at the end, quietly making the case for who he is before the genre was even a consideration. It's the most honest track on the record, and it sounds exactly like someone with the lights off, working out what the instrument can hold.\n\nAllastair Voss\n\n\nThe debut album proves the project is real, built to last beyond the initial critical moment, capable of development rather than repetition. UK garage has been waiting for this kind of harmonic ambition for a decade. Lockerz arrived at exactly the right time, with exactly the right training, to give it what it needed.\n\nThe critical conversation around the record has focused on the jazz piano angle, which is the right conversation to be having, but it risks underselling the quality of the drums. The two-step sits at exactly the right tempo for the material: not too fast to lose the harmonic movement, not slow enough to feel reflective rather than dancefloor-ready. That tempo judgment is its own kind of skill, and it reflects someone who has internalized the form deeply enough to know exactly where to place it for maximum effect. The piano and the drums earn each other. Neither would work without the other being exactly as good as it is.\n[download:/assets/images/artists/lockerz-jazz-piano-garage-social-9x16.jpg|Download Social Card]",
  "description": "Lockerz is a Welsh producer who came up through drum and bass before deciding the swung two-step was a more interesting place to spend a decade. He is",
  "image_alt": "Lockerz brings jazz piano to UK garage"
}
ENDJSON
echo 'Expanded: lockerz-jazz-piano-garage.json'

# ---- POST: lolo-zouai-reverie ----
