{
  "title": "Loraine James: The Restless Center",
  "category": "music",
  "author": "Allastair Voss",
  "date": "2026-04-27",
  "image": "/assets/images/artists/loraine-james.jpg",
  "body": "Loraine James grew up in Enfield, North London, on a steady diet of math rock and post-rock and the kind of electronic records that don't ask you to dance so much as ask you to keep up. That sensibility, restless without being chaotic, has become a signature across her catalogue. From For You And I in 2019 to Reflection in 2021 and Gentle Confrontation in 2023, James has built a body of work that resists genre even while sounding completely coherent.\n\nHer tracks behave more like passages than songs. They turn corners. They open into rooms you didn't see coming. On Reflection, the title track folds glitchy percussion into something unexpectedly tender, and the result feels less like a producer flexing and more like a thought being followed to its end. Building Something Beautiful For Me, her 2022 record dedicated to the composer Julius Eastman, made that approach explicit by treating composition itself as a form of attention. Eastman was a composer who worked in minimalist repetition with a ferocity that undermined the genre's reputation for placidity: his work was politically charged, physically demanding to perform, deeply personal. James's dedication to him was not nostalgic homage. It was a claim about lineage and method.\n\n[spotify:artist/536qHynzDH1QviwhWY9dE3]\n\n## The Hyperdub Lineage\n\nBeing on Hyperdub means being part of a lineage that includes Burial and DJ Rashad and a long history of artists who don't pander to the dance floor and don't run from it either. James fits that lineage because her music holds two things at once: the rhythmic insistence of footwork and dancehall, and the harmonic patience of contemporary classical. The friction between those modes is what makes her records feel alive. The Hyperdub catalogue is built on artists who understand that the club and the concert hall are not opposites. They're two different versions of the same question: how much can a room hold?\n\nWhatever the Weather, her ambient pseudonym, gave her a separate channel for slower work. Releases under that name operate differently: more patient, less percussive, closer to the texture of long duration listening. The split is useful because it lets the main project keep its tension. James the producer doesn't need to soothe. The Whatever the Weather records are where she allows that, and the separation keeps both channels cleaner. In 2025 she returned to the Whatever the Weather name for a second volume.\n\n## Detached From The Rest Of You\n\nDetached From The Rest Of You arrived May 2026 and it's her most interior record. Where Gentle Confrontation was aggressive in its formal choices, this one is stripped: clicks and glitches drawing on the early 2000s clicks-and-cuts tradition of Aoki Takamasa and Ryoji Ikeda, the pointillist electronic music that made silence as load-bearing as sound. James half-jokingly calls it her IDM popstar album, and the joke contains the truth: the production is spare enough to feel like solo piano, while the guest appearances from Alan Sparhawk, Tirzah, and Miho Hatori arrive in that stripped space without trying to fill it.\n\nFollowing Gentle Confrontation, James found herself overthinking and struggling with self-doubt, and this record leans into that confidence crisis rather than transcending it. The album is not a resolution. It's a document of the doubt, which is a braver thing to make than a document of recovery. Doubt documented with this much formal precision is its own kind of confidence.\n\nThe production on Detached is stripped to essentials: the sounds are named and placed with the care of someone who believes that a click at the right moment carries as much weight as a chord. The record is quiet in a way that requires volume to hear properly. At low volume it disappears; at high volume it becomes something else entirely.\n\n## What's Next\n\nHyperdub releases tend to mark turning points in an artist's trajectory. This one feels like another. James has built a body of work that is already substantial enough to have its own internal logic, its own way of reading each new release against the ones before. At each step she has changed something fundamental while staying recognizably herself. The restless center holds.\n\n## The Clicks-and-Cuts Tradition and Its Legacy\n\nThe clicks-and-cuts genre that James references on Detached emerged from a very specific moment in early 2000s electronic music, when producers like Alva Noto, Ryoji Ikeda, and Aoki Takamasa began treating digital artifacts, the sounds that computers make when they fail or are pushed beyond their intended parameters, as compositional material. The aesthetic was severe, minimal, and deliberately inhospitable to casual listening. You had to meet it on its own terms.\n\nJames's version of this approach is warmer than the originals. The clicks and glitches sit in arrangements that still have emotional color: the Julius Eastman influence softening the harder edges of the tradition, the R&B and soul background providing harmonic warmth that the purely digital tradition lacked. What she has done is take a cold aesthetic and warm it from the inside without canceling what made it interesting in the first place.\n\nThe guest vocalists on Detached, Tirzah in particular, bring a fragility to the stripped-down environment that the original clicks-and-cuts tradition would never have accommodated. Tirzah's voice is already a study in controlled vulnerability: thin, slightly distant, always sounding like it might not survive the song. Placed inside James's pointillist production, it becomes something else: the human element in a world of precise digital sounds, the warmth that the clicks-and-cuts tradition always needed but didn't know how to ask for.\n\n\nThe restless center is the thing about her work that draws continued attention. Most artists find their sound and mine it. James keeps moving the sound. The center, her specific intelligence and formal commitment, holds while everything around it shifts. That combination of stability and restlessness is what makes her body of work distinctive: you never know what the next record will sound like, but you always know it will be hers. Detached From The Rest Of You is the current record. Whatever comes after it will be different from this, and different in a direction she has not yet announced. That is the only thing that can be said with confidence about her trajectory, and it is sufficient.\n[download:/assets/images/artists/loraine-james-restless-center-social-9x16.jpg|Download Social Card]",
  "description": "Loraine James grew up in Enfield, North London, on a steady diet of math rock and post-rock and the kind of electronic records that don't ask you to dance",
  "image_alt": "Loraine James: The Restless Center"
}
ENDJSON
echo 'Expanded: loraine-james-restless-center.json'

